ystem: queued %d deposit(s) for respawn in '%s'\" % [\n121-\t\t\t\tdepleted.size(), departed_biome])\n122-\t\t# Always mark biome departed, even if nothing was depleted.\n123-\t\t_departed_biomes[departed_biome] = true\n124-\n125-\t# -- Arrival logic --","numLines":16}},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01F2F1LsyvTR4wyKwLTjbWwx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The resource respawn system's `_on_biome_changed` doesn't seem problematic - it just manages respawn data.\n\nLet me look at this from yet another angle. Let me look at what `_on_travel_completed` logs. If I add some targeted logging, I could figure out what's happening. But since this is a code bug that I need to fix, let me try to reason about it more carefully.\n\nLet me focus on the Godot 4 `await` behavior for coroutines. Here's the key thing:\n\nIn `_on_travel_completed`, the function is a coroutine (it has multiple `await` statements). When called as a signal handler, what happens?\n\n\nWhen a coroutine is connected to a signal in Godot 4, it starts executing when the signal fires, but pauses at the first `await` - allowing the signal emission to return and subsequent code to run before the coroutine resumes. So in `initiate_travel()`, the `travel_completed` signal starts the coroutine, which pauses at its first await, then `biome_changed` emits before `_on_travel_completed` continues executing. This ordering is actually fine.\n\nNow I'm thinking through what might actually be causing the issue. The problem could be with the tween in `_fade_out()` - for it to complete, the node needs to be processing, have the right process mode, and be in the scene tree. I'm wondering if `TravelSequenceManager` is getting removed from the tree during `_clear_biome_container()`, which would prevent the tween from finishing and break the await chain.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, `_clear_biome_container()` only removes children of the biome container itself, not the TravelSequenceManager which is a child of TestWorld, so that's probably not it. Let me consider whether the issue is with tween creation itself - maybe `_close_for_travel()` creates a tween on the NavigationConsole that completes before the fade tween, causing something to break in the sequence.\n\nWait, I'm realizing that in Godot 4, creating a new tween on a node automatically kills any previous tweens on that node. But since this should be the first tween on TravelSequenceManager, that shouldn't be the problem. Let me check if the fade rect itself might be invalid - perhaps `_build_fade_overlay()` was called but the fade layer got freed somehow, even though it's a child of TravelSequenceManager and nothing should be removing it.\n\nActually, looking at how `_build_fade_overlay()` constructs the fade layer and rect...\n\nSetting up the fade overlay... I'm tracing through the confirm flow — when the player confirms travel, it emits the signal, closes the UI, and tells the navigation system to start the journey. But I notice `_close_for_travel()` seems to cut off mid-function, so let me see what happens after it sets the mouse mode and triggers the close animation.\n\nLooking at `_animate_close()`, it creates a tween that fades out both the dim overlay and main panel in parallel over 0.15 seconds, then hides the panel when complete. The issue is that with `set_parallel(true)`, the callback gets scheduled at t=0 alongside the animations, but Godot tweens don't process until the next frame, so the visibility might change before the fade actually completes visually.\n\nNow I'm tracing through what happens when the confirm button is pressed and `_on_confirm_pressed()` executes in the context of Godot's signal handling.\n\nThe method runs synchronously: `_close_for_travel()` executes, then `initiate_travel()` runs and immediately emits `travel_completed`, which triggers `_on_travel_completed()` right away. That method runs until it hits the `await _fade_out()` call, which starts a tween and waits for it to finish. Since the tween just started, the await suspends `_on_travel_completed()`, which means control returns back up through the call stack to `_on_confirm_pressed()`. Meanwhile, the tween runs for 0.5 seconds, and when it finishes...\n\nThe tween emits its finished signal, `_fade_out()` resumes and returns, which lets `_on_travel_completed()` continue past the await. Then `execute_biome_swap()` runs to load the new biome, followed by `await _fade_in()`, and finally input gets re-enabled.\n\nI can't pinpoint the bug just by tracing through the logic, so let me think about this differently. What if `_on_travel_completed()` is actually running, the `_fade_out()` does create the tween, but the tween's node isn't processing for some reason? Let me check if TravelSequenceManager has the right process mode set.\n\nLooking at the class definition, there's no explicit process_mode, so it inherits from its parent TestWorld, which is a Node3D with no explicit setting either. Everything should be cascading down as PROCESS_MODE_INHERIT, which should work fine.\n\nLet me examine the `_on_travel_sequence_started` handler in test_world more closely to see if something there could be interfering. It just sets `_transitioning = true`, which shouldn't pause anything. But I should check whether `_transitioning` is being used in `_process` or `_input` to block execution.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":444,"cache_read_input_tokens":87686,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":444},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"6ad6ab0d-915d-4cc4-a577-1c360c4be8af"},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01F2F1LsyvTR4wyKw