hip from interior exit zone\n   373→\tif _ship_interior.is_player_inside() and _ship_interior.is_player_in_exit_zone():\n   374→\t\tif InputManager.is_action_just_pressed(\"interact\"):\n   375→\t\t\t_begin_exit_ship()\n   376→\t\t\treturn\n   377→\n   378→\t# Interact with ship interior objects when inside\n   379→\tif _ship_interior.is_player_inside():\n   380→\t\tif InputManager.is_action_just_pressed(\"interact\"):\n   381→\t\t\t# Check cockpit navigation console\n   382→\t\t\tif _ship_interior.is_player_near_cockpit_console():\n   383→\t\t\t\tif _navigation_console:\n   384→\t\t\t\t\t_navigation_console.open_panel()\n   385→\t\t\t\treturn\n   386→\t\t\t# Check terminal\n   387→\t\t\tif _ship_interior.is_player_near_terminal():\n   388→\t\t\t\t_tech_tree_panel.open()\n   389→\t\t\t\treturn\n   390→\t\t\t# Check placement zones\n   391→\t\t\tvar zone_index: int = _ship_interior.get_nearby_zone_index()\n   392→\t\t\tif zone_index >= 0:\n   393→\t\t\t\tif _ship_interior.is_zone_occupied(zone_index):\n   394→\t\t\t\t\t_open_module_panel(zone_index)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"8a9faa98-571e-44ab-a416-ac1ad1f138de","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"C:\\repos\\Hammer-Forge-Studio\\.claude\\worktrees\\orch-gameplay-programmer-TICKET-0247\\game\\scripts\\levels\\test_world.gd","content":"\tif _transitioning or not _ship_interior:\n\t\treturn\n\tif _travel_manager and _travel_manager.is_transitioning():\n\t\treturn\n\n\t# Don't process interact while a UI panel is open\n\tif _module_placement_ui and _module_placement_ui.is_open():\n\t\treturn\n\tif _recycler_panel and _recycler_panel.is_open():\n\t\treturn\n\tif _tech_tree_panel and _tech_tree_panel.is_open():\n\t\treturn\n\tif _fabricator_panel and _fabricator_panel.is_open():\n\t\treturn\n\tif _automation_hub_panel and _automation_hub_panel.is_open():\n\t\treturn\n\tif _navigation_console and _navigation_console.is_open():\n\t\treturn\n\tif _inventory_screen and _inventory_screen.is_open():\n\t\treturn\n\n\t# Enter ship from exterior\n\tif _player_near_ship_entrance and not _ship_interior.is_player_inside():\n\t\tif InputManager.is_action_just_pressed(\"interact\"):\n\t\t\t_begin_enter_ship()\n\t\t\treturn\n\n\t# Exit ship from interior exit zone\n\tif _ship_interior.is_player_inside() and _ship_interior.is_player_in_exit_zone():\n\t\tif InputManager.is_action_just_pressed(\"interact\"):\n\t\t\t_begin_exit_ship()\n\t\t\treturn\n\n\t# Interact with ship interior objects when inside\n\tif _ship_interior.is_player_inside():\n\t\tif InputManager.is_action_just_pressed(\"interact\"):\n\t\t\t# Check cockpit navigation console\n\t\t\tif _ship_interior.is_player_near_cockpit_console():\n\t\t\t\tif _navigation_console:\n\t\t\t\t\t_navigation_console.open_panel()\n\t\t\t\treturn\n\t\t\t# Check terminal\n\t\t\tif _ship_interior.is_player_near_terminal():\n\t\t\t\t_tech_tree_panel.open()\n\t\t\t\treturn\n\t\t\t# Check placement zones\n\t\t\tvar zone_index: int = _ship_interior.get_nearby_zone_index()\n\t\t\tif zone_index >= 0:\n\t\t\t\tif _ship_interior.is_zone_occupied(zone_index):\n\t\t\t\t\t_open_module_panel(zone_index)","numLines":50,"startLine":345,"totalLines":649}}},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01TwS23vMEScLPsJK6bFibdL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `_transitioning` flag is used in `_update_ship_interact()` to prevent interactions during transitions. But it doesn't pause processing or affect tweens.\n\nLet me look at this from a completely different angle. Let me re-read the producer's debugging guidance more carefully:\n\n> Verify that NavigationSystem.initiate_travel() actually emits travel_completed after fuel is consumed — add logging if needed.\n\nThe producer suspects `initiate_travel()` might not be emitting `travel_completed`. Let me look at it again:\n\n```gdscript\nfunc initiate_travel(destination_id: String) -> void:\tif _state != TravelState.IDLE:\n\n\n```\n\nExamining the travel initiation flow...\n\nThe function validates the destination, checks travel eligibility, consumes fuel, and transitions through the state machine from PREPARING to IN_TRANSIT to ARRIVING. I need to see where `travel_completed` actually gets emitted in this sequence.\n\nLooking at the fuel consumption side effect — when `FuelSystem.consume_fuel()` fires the `fuel_changed` signal, the NavigationConsole's callback won't do anything since it's closed during travel. But the FuelGauge is also listening to that same signal, so I should check what happens there.\n\nActually, let me refocus on the core issue the producer flagged. The biome transition isn't happening at all, which means either `initiate_travel()` is returning early before emitting `travel_completed`, or `_on_travel_completed()` is hitting its own early return. I should systematically check each condition that could cause `initiate_travel()` to bail out.\n\nThe state check seems unlikely since the state machine always cycles back to IDLE. The biome validity check should pass since the UI only shows registered biomes. The current biome filter should prevent selecting where we already are. That leaves the `can_travel_to()` check as the most suspicious candidate.\n\nThere's a potential race condition here: the navigation console checks fuel availability before enabling the button, but the fuel state could theoretically change between that check and when `initiate_travel()` runs its own `can_travel_to()` validation. Though in practice, the player isn't consuming fuel while the console is open, so this seems unlikely too. Let me trace through the exact sequence of calls to see if there's a window where something could go wrong. Looking at `_on_travel_completed` more carefully, I see it sets a transitioning flag, emits the travel sequence started signal, disables gameplay inputs, then fades to black before executing the biome swap. The function appears to be cut off mid-execution, but the key point is that this is where the actual travel sequence begins after the panel closes.\n\nNow I'm wondering if the issue is that the biome swap itself is failing silently—the function returns a bool indicating success or failure, and if it fails, there's an error recovery path that re-enables inputs and resets the transitioning flag. But what if the swap is actually succeeding and the fade-in is happening, yet the player still doesn't see the new biome?\n\nActually, I should check what could cause the swap to crash rather than fail gracefully. If an exception is thrown during the swap, the coroutine would be interrupted, leaving the transitioning state locked and inputs disabled. Let me trace through the biome creation logic to see where that might happen. So if the fade overlay was never built, that would explain the \"no fade\" symptom, and if `execute_biome_swap` crashes afterward, inputs would stay locked and the scene wouldn't change. That matches the producer's report perfectly. The node should be in the tree when `setup()` is called based on the test code, so `_build_fade_overlay()` should work — unless the fade rect gets freed somehow later. Let me focus on what's actually happening: the player is stuck in place and the biome transition never starts at all.\n\nActually, maybe this is simpler than I'm thinking. What if `_on_travel_completed` runs but the `await` inside it doesn't resume properly? In Godot 4, when a signal emits and the connected function is a coroutine with an `await`, the coroutine suspends and the signal emission returns immediately. The coroutine resumes when the awaited condition is met. But I'm wondering if there's something about how the `travel_completed` signal is connected on the `NavigationSystem` autoload that's preventing the coroutine from resuming correctly.\n\nLet me trace through this more carefully. The signal connection is straightforward—`NavigationSystem.travel_completed` connects to `TravelSequenceManager._on_travel_completed`. When the signal fires, the method starts, hits the `await`, suspends, and the signal emission returns. The tween created in `_fade_out()` should run on the `TravelSequenceManager` instance in the tree, finish, and then the coroutine resumes. This should work fine, but clearly something isn't happening.\n\nI'm going in circles here. I need to actually run the scene and see what's happening, but I can't do that. Let me go back to the debugging guidance and think about what's actually observable.\n\nThe producer is asking whether closing the panel before `initiate_travel()` affects any node references or signal connections that `TravelSequenceManager` relies on. Looking at `_close_for_travel()`, it sets `_is_open` to false, captures the mouse, creates a tween on `NavigationConsole`, and emits `panel_closed`. None of that should touch `TravelSequenceManager`'s references or connections.\n\nThe other clue is about confirming that `TravelSequenceManager` is in the scene tree and its handler is connected when travel is initiated. The connection happens in `setup()`, so I need to verify whether that's actually being called and whether the node is still in the tree at the right time.\n\nNow I'm realizing something critical: in Godot 4, if a tween is bound to a node and that node gets freed or removed from the tree, the tween is killed and its `finished` signal never fires. That would cause `await tween.finished` to hang indefinitely. The only awaits in this flow are on tween completion, so if a tween's node is being removed, the entire sequence would stall. `TravelSequenceManager` itself isn't being removed, but I need to check whether the `_fade` tween or any other tween's node is being freed prematurely. The tween binds to TravelSequenceManager via `create_tween()`, so it should process fine as long as the node stays in the tree. Let me think through what could actually prevent the `finished` signal from firing — the tween getting killed when the node exits the tree, being paused indefinitely, or the tree itself being paused, but none of those seem to be happening here.\n\nCould `create_tween()` itself be failing silently, or maybe the tween is created but the tweener is invalid? I know `create_tween()` returns null if the node isn't in the tree, but we're checking `is_inside_tree()` first, so that shouldn't be the issue. Let me look back at the actual `_fade_out()` implementation to see what's really going on.\n\nActually, I'm noticing something — what if `_fade_rect` exists but `is_inside_tree()` returns false when `_fade_out()` is called? That would mean TravelSequenceManager got removed from the tree between setup and the fade, but I already ruled that out. And even if it did happen, signal callbacks execute in the normal call stack, so `is_inside_tree()` would reflect the actual state at that moment.\n\nI'm going in circles here. Let me check if the signal connection itself might be the culprit.\n\nWait, I should verify whether `NavigationSystem` is actually the autoload singleton or if there's a naming mismatch somewhere.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3294,"cache_read_input_tokens":88130,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3294},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"5af51ef6-2a24-4ee1-bcf5-1d0c65c5e90b"},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01TwS23vMEScLPsJK6bFibdL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01BTA5FNN3JnU67gjurq7c7p","name":"Grep","input":{"pattern":"NavigationSystem","path":"C:\\repos\\Hammer-Forge-Studio\\.claude\\worktrees\\orch-gameplay-programmer-TICKET-0247\\game","glob":"project.godot","output_mode":"content","