own()\nC:\\repos\\Hammer-Forge-Studio\\.claude\\worktrees\\orch-gameplay-programmer-TICKET-0247\\game\\tests\\test_collision_coverage_unit.gd:34:\t\t_probe.teardown()","numLines":2}},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_016hF2c48Nv1GkTi9fW5R6Pn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good — `teardown()` is only called in the test suite's `after_each()`. It's never called in the actual game. So the signal stays connected.\n\nNow let me focus on hypothesis #2: `initiate_travel()` hits an early return.\n\nLet me check each condition:1. `_state != TravelState.IDLE` — starts as IDLE, only changed by `initiate_travel()` itself. If `initiate_travel()` hasn't been called before, it's IDLE.2. `not BiomeRegistry.is_valid_biome(destination_id)` — destination comes from the navigation console, which only shows valid biomes.\n\n\n3. `destination_id == current_biome` — the navigation console filters out the current biome, so this shouldn't trigger.4. `not can_travel_to(destination_id)` — already validated in `_on_confirm_pressed` at line 709.\n\nWait, I need to reconsider #3. On the first call to `initiate_travel()`, `current_biome` defaults to \"shattered_flats\", and the player picks a different biome like \"rock_warrens\", so that check should pass.\n\nActually, I'm wondering if the issue is that `_on_confirm_pressed()` is being invoked twice from a single button press. If that happens, the first call closes the dialog and starts the travel sequence, but the second call might find that fuel was already consumed, making `can_travel_to()` return false.\n\nBut even if `initiate_travel()` somehow fires again, the state machine would already be at IDLE after the first call completes its synchronous transitions, and `destination_id` would equal `current_biome`, causing an early return. Plus, `_on_travel_completed` checks `_is_transitioning` to prevent duplicate processing, so a second signal wouldn't cause issues there either.\n\nLet me trace through `_on_confirm_pressed()` more carefully to find the actual bug. I'm checking the function logic...\n\nExamining the confirm button handler...\n\nThe function validates the selection, emits a signal, closes the UI, and initiates travel to the destination. The flow looks correct at first glance — it checks that a biome is selected and that travel is affordable before proceeding.\n\nNow I'm double-checking the `initiate_travel()` function to see if there's something I'm missing. It validates the state, checks that the destination is valid, prevents traveling to the current biome, verifies we can afford it, then transitions to preparing and consumes fuel before moving to in-transit.\n\nWait, I see it now — when `FuelSystem.consume_fuel()` fires the `fuel_changed` signal, the NavigationConsole's handler runs even though `_is_open` is false, so the guard clause prevents any actual refresh from happening.\n\nBut the FuelGauge is also listening to that same signal, and I need to check what its handler actually does — it's probably just updating UI elements, which shouldn't interfere with the travel sequence.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the whole problem. What if the issue isn't in the travel flow at all, but in how the biome scene loads when `execute_biome_swap()` calls `create_biome_node(destination_id)`?\n\nWhen that new biome node gets added to the container, its `_ready()` method might be throwing an error that's silently killing the coroutine. Let me look at the biome class implementations to see what's happening there.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2257,"cache_read_input_tokens":105028,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2257},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","u