ead_input_tokens":107285,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1911},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"b900f179-11bb-45da-aca9-e75269a1b519"},{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014nSHuPyKhcXR4juc85BfEZ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→## Rock Warrens biome — dense rock formations creating tight navigable corridors\n     2→## with low visibility. Mixed resource profile: Scrap Metal and Cryonite pockets.\n     3→## Must contain sufficient resources to craft at least one Fuel Cell.\n     4→## Owner: gameplay-programmer\n     5→class_name RockWarrensBiome\n     6→extends Node3D\n     7→\n     8→\n     9→# ── Signals ──────────────────────────────────────────────\n    10→\n    11→signal generation_completed\n    12→\n    13→\n    14→# ── Constants ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n    15→\n    16→## Fixed seed for deterministic terrain generation (from BiomeRegistry).\n    17→const BIOME_SEED: int = 2047\n    18→\n    19→## Terrain extent in metres.\n    20→const TERRAIN_SIZE: float = 500.0\n    21→\n    22→## Ship/player spawn clearing radius in metres.\n    23→const SHIP_CLEARING_RADIUS: float = 20.0\n    24→\n    25→## Walkable clearance radius around resource positions in metres.\n    26→const RESOURCE_CLEARANCE_RADIUS: float = 3.0\n    27→\n    28→## Maximum terrain slope for resource placement (degrees).\n    29→const RESOURCE_SLOPE_MAX: float = 30.0\n    30→\n    31→## Minimum spacing between resource positions (metres).\n    32→const RESOURCE_SPACING: float = 15.0\n    33→\n    34→## Scrap Metal surface deposit count range per acceptance criteria.\n    35→const SCRAP_METAL_SURFACE_MIN: int = 5\n    36→const SCRAP_METAL_SURFACE_MAX: int = 8\n    37→\n    38→## Cryonite surface deposit count range per acceptance criteria.\n    39→const CRYONITE_SURFACE_MIN: int = 4\n    40→const CRYONITE_SURFACE_MAX: int = 7\n    41→\n    42→## Number of deep nodes per resource type.\n    43→const DEEP_NODES_PER_TYPE: int = 1\n    44→\n    45→## Deep node quantity — high value; infinite flag means it never depletes.\n    46→const DEEP_NODE_QUANTITY: int = 100\n    47→\n    48→## Surface deposit quantity range.\n    49→const SURFACE_NODE_MIN_QUANTITY: int = 15\n    50→const SURFACE_NODE_MAX_QUANTITY: int = 40\n    51→\n    52→## Deep node yield rate multiplier (10% of surface speed).\n    53→const DEEP_NODE_YIELD_RATE: float = 0.1\n    54→\n    55→## Rock formation grid spacing — metres between formation placement checks.\n    56→const FORMATION_GRID_SPACING: float = 12.0\n    57→\n    58→## Exclusion radius around spawn and resource positions — no formations placed here.\n    59→const FORMATION_EXCLUSION_RADIUS: float = 6.0\n    60→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"ea4f1318-658b-49c1-81c5-e0813cd101da","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"C:\\repos\\Hammer-Forge-Studio\\.claude\\worktrees\\orch-gameplay-programmer-TICKET-0247\\game\\scripts\\gameplay\\rock_warrens_biome.gd","content":"## Rock Warrens biome — dense rock formations creating tight navigable corridors\n## with low visibility. Mixed resource profile: Scrap Metal and Cryonite pockets.\n## Must contain sufficient resources to craft at least one Fuel Cell.\n## Owner: gameplay-programmer\nclass_name RockWarrensBiome\nextends Node3D\n\n\n# ── Signals ──────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nsignal generation_completed\n\n\n# ── Constants ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n## Fixed seed for deterministic terrain generation (from BiomeRegistry).\nconst BIOME_SEED: int = 2047\n\n## Terrain extent in metres.\nconst TERRAIN_SIZE: float = 500.0\n\n## Ship/player spawn clearing radius in metres.\nconst SHIP_CLEARING_RADIUS: float = 20.0\n\n## Walkable clearance radius around resource positions in metres.\nconst RESOURCE_CLEARANCE_RADIUS: float = 3.0\n\n## Maximum terrain slope for resource placement (degrees).\nconst RESOURCE_SLOPE_MAX: float = 30.0\n\n## Minimum spacing between resource positions (metres).\nconst RESOURCE_SPACING: float = 15.0\n\n## Scrap Metal surface deposit count range per acceptance criteria.\nconst SCRAP_METAL_SURFACE_MIN: int = 5\nconst SCRAP_METAL_SURFACE_MAX: int = 8\n\n## Cryonite surface deposit count range per acceptance criteria.\nconst CRYONITE_SURFACE_MIN: int = 4\nconst CRYONITE_SURFACE_MAX: int = 7\n\n## Number of deep nodes per resource type.\nconst DEEP_NODES_PER_TYPE: int = 1\n\n## Deep node quantity — high value; infinite flag means it never depletes.\nconst DEEP_NODE_QUANTITY: int = 100\n\n## Surface deposit quantity range.\nconst SURFACE_NODE_MIN_QUANTITY: int = 15\nconst SURFACE_NODE_MAX_QUANTITY: int = 40\n\n## Deep node yield rate multiplier (10% of surface speed).\nconst DEEP_NODE_YIELD_RATE: float = 0.1\n\n## Rock formation grid spacing — metres between formation placement checks.\nconst FORMATION_GRID_SPACING: float = 12.0\n\n## Exclusion radius around spawn and resource positions — no formations placed here.\nconst FORMATION_EXCLUSION_RADIUS: float = 6.0\n","numLines":60,"startLine":1,"totalLines":612}}},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_019y3qL5unbS4EzoJcN7yBYi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK let me look at the `generate()` method and `_ready()` of this biome to see if there's anything that could crash.\n\nActually, wait. I've been spending a lot of time investigating this. Let me reconsider the problem from the producer's debugging notes:\n\n> The input lock confirms _close_for_travel() ran and NavigationSystem.initiate_travel() was called (since the input disable happens inside TravelSequenceManager._on_travel_completed, which is connected to the travel_completed signal).\n\nThe producer ASSUMES the input lock is from TravelSequenceManager._on_travel_completed, but it could also be just from NavigationConsole.open_panel() + _close_for_travel() not re-enabling inputs.\n \nSo I need to check if _fade_out() could be hanging or returning early in the handler, which would leave inputs locked while the transition stalls. I should also verify that NavigationSystem.initiate_travel() actually emits the travel_completed signal after fuel is consumed—might need to add logging to confirm. And I'm wondering if closing the panel before initiate_travel() (the wave 2 reorder) could be breaking node references or signal connections that TravelSequenceManager depends on.\n\nLet me also make sure TravelSequenceManager is actually in the scene tree and its handler is properly connected when travel gets initiated. There's also the possibility of an await silently stalling—like if a timer or coroutine races with a freed node.\n\nActually, stepping back—I've been overcomplicating this. What if the real issue is something simpler, like a Godot 4 quirk where awaiting a coroutine that returns early from inside a signal handler causes everything to hang? Let me reconsider what actually changed.\n\nThe wave 2 reorder moved `_close_for_travel()` before `initiate_travel()`. Before that change, the sequence was calling `initiate_travel()` first (which fires travel_completed and starts the fade-out await), then closing the panel and re-enabling inputs—which was actually working, just with that input bug. After the reorder, we're closing the panel first without re-enabling inputs, then calling `initiate_travel()`. The transition broke after this change, so the difference must be in how `initiate_travel()` is being called or what state the system is in when it fires.\n\nI'm wondering if closing the panel first could somehow interfere with the fuel check in `can_travel_to()`, but that doesn't make sense since fuel hasn't changed. Actually, I should look at what happens when `initiate_travel()` consumes fuel—that triggers the `_on_fuel_changed` handler in NavigationConsole, which only refreshes the UI if the panel is open. Since we're now closing the panel before initiating travel, the handler might be behaving differently when it fires. So after the travel completes, `travel_completed` gets emitted and triggers the transition animation. Looking at both scenarios, the flow is essentially the same—whether the UI updates during fuel consumption or gets skipped entirely doesn't affect the outcome since the panel closes anyway. But I'm realizing there might be something else I'm missing here.\n\nIn the old flow, `_refresh_detail()` gets called during fuel consumption, which checks if the player can still afford travel by calling `can_travel_to()`. After fuel is consumed, this might return false and disable the button, but again, that's irrelevant since the panel is already closing. Though `can_travel_to()` itself does something I need to trace through...\n\nActually, I'm realizing the wave 2 change doesn't actually affect the travel mechanics themselves—it's just a UI timing difference. So the real bug has to be elsewhere. Let me step back and think about this differently. Maybe the issue is with autoload initialization order? `NavigationSystem` is one of the last regular autoloads, but `TravelSequenceManager` isn't an autoload at all, so there could be a dependency problem there.\n\nWait, let me verify the setup. `NavigationSystem` is the autoload singleton that `TravelSequenceManager` connects to via signal, and `NavigationConsole` calls methods on the same singleton. The signal connection and emission are definitely happening on the same object, so that's not the issue.\n\nLet me explore another angle—could there be a Godot 4 quirk where coroutines don't resume properly when awaiting a tween that's created inside a signal handler? The call stack is pretty deep here: button press triggers the confirm handler, which eventually calls `initiate_travel`, which emits the signal, which calls `_on_travel_completed`, which creates a tween and awaits it. That shouldn't cause problems in Godot 4, but what if the tween's finished signal fires before the coroutine is fully set up?\n\nActually, that can't be it—the tween doesn't start processing until the next frame, and the coroutine setup happens synchronously in the current frame.\n\nLet me check if there's a process_mode issue. The TravelSequenceManager inherits its process mode from TestWorld, but tweens created with `create_tween()` default to `TWEEN_PROCESS_IDLE`, which should be fine for UI animations. Could idle processing be blocked somehow? No, the game is running normally—the player can see the world, so process steps are definitely happening.\n\nI've been circling this for too long. Let me take a step back and look for something more concrete.\n\nI'm wondering if `create_tween()` could return null in some edge case. It requires the node to be in the scene tree, and we do check `is_inside_tree()` first. But what if that check passes and `create_tween()` still fails? The only way I can think of is if `get_tree()` returns null during the call—which could happen if the node is being freed—but that seems unlikely given the timing.\n\nLet me reconsider the signal connection itself. I'm looking at how `_on_travel_completed` is connected to the `travel_completed` signal, and I'm realizing there might be an issue with the connection flags. The default connection has no special flags, which means the callback fires immediately rather than deferred, and it doesn't automatically disconnect after firing.\n\nActually, I'm now wondering if the real problem is that `_on_travel_completed` uses `await` inside the signal handler, and maybe the continuation after the await isn't resuming properly in Godot 4. This is supposed to work, but there might be a specific edge case I'm missing.\n\nIn Godot 4, when a signal handler is a coroutine and the signal fires synchronously, the coroutine runs until its first `await`, then gets scheduled to resume later—but only if the object owning the coroutine still exists. Since TravelSequenceManager isn't being freed during this flow, the continuation should persist.\n\nLet me check if `create_tween()` might be killing itself somehow, though that seems unlikely since there shouldn't be any previous tweens on this node to clear out.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the difference between Godot 3 and 4 here. In Godot 4, `create_tween()` doesn't automatically kill previous tweens—multiple tweens can run on the same node simultaneously. So that's not the issue.\n\nMy best guess is that the problem only manifests in the actual game when the fade overlay is present. In unit tests, `_fade_rect` is null so `_fade_out()` returns immediately and the await resolves right away, letting `execute_biome_swap()` run and load the biome. But in the game, `_fade_rect` exists, which means something different happens in that code path.\n\nLet me trace through what `execute_biome_swap()` actually does—it creates a new biome node, validates it, clears the old biome container, and adds the new biome as a child.\n\nThe key difference I'm noticing is that in the test, `_biome_container` isn't part of the scene tree, so when the biome gets added as a child, it's not actually being rendered or initialized properly. In the actual game, `_biome_container` is `_biome_content` which is already in the tree, so the biome loads correctly.\n\nBut wait — the real symptom is that the fade doesn't happen at all, which means the problem is earlier in the chain. I'm wondering if `_on_travel_completed` never fires because `initiate_travel()` is hitting an early return before the signal even gets emitted. Let me add some logging to trace whether that's actually happening.\n\nActually, let me look at the `_on_confirm_pressed` function more carefully. It checks if a biome is selected and if travel is affordable, then emits the signal, closes the UI, and calls `initiate_travel()`. The logging statements should help me see which of these steps is actually executing versus which ones are being skipped.\n\nNow I'm looking at the `initiate_travel` function to see what validation it does before actually starting the travel sequence. It checks the travel state, validates the destination biome exists, prevents traveling to the current biome, and blocks travel if the player can't afford it. The function appears to be cut off mid-log message, but I can see it's doing several guard checks before proceeding with the actual travel logic.\n\nI'm wondering if there's a race condition happening with the fuel consumption. When `consume_fuel` is called, it emits a signal that handlers respond to synchronously, but looking at what those handlers do—the NavigationConsole is just a no-op and the FuelGauge only updates the UI—there shouldn't be anything that would trigger a re-entrant call back into `initiate_travel`. Let me check what other signals `consume_fuel` might be emitting that could cause issues.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":907,"cache_read_input_tokens":109196,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":907},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"912189a3-5ad4-425d-bece-59e8717e87b3"},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_019y3qL5unbS4EzoJcN7yBYi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01YTLGudapLAK74G7FDo11Ds","name":"Grep","input":{"pattern":"fuel_low\\.connect|fuel_empty\\.connect","glob":"*.gd","output_mode":"content","-n":true},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":907,"cache_read_input_tok