standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"47e5807a-ec2a-43ae-8107-acf8c3798067"},{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013L4P3ea6x87JjtMxeYAuv4","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→## Fuel gauge HUD: always-visible ship fuel level display with state-driven colors.\n     2→## Connects to FuelSystem signals (fuel_changed, fuel_low, fuel_empty) for real-time updates.\n     3→## Four visual states: full (green), normal (teal), low (amber pulse), empty (coral flash).\n     4→## Owner: gameplay-programmer — Ticket: TICKET-0169\n     5→class_name FuelGauge\n     6→extends Control\n     7→\n     8→# ── Constants ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n     9→const BAR_WIDTH: float = 160.0\n    10→const BAR_HEIGHT: float = 10.0\n    11→const ICON_SIZE: float = 24.0\n    12→const TOTAL_WIDTH: float = 200.0\n    13→const TOTAL_HEIGHT: float = 48.0\n    14→const LOW_THRESHOLD: float = FuelSystemDefs.LOW_FUEL_THRESHOLD_PERCENT\n    15→const PULSE_SPEED: float = 4.2  # ~1.5s loop (2*PI / 1.5)\n    16→const FLASH_INTERVAL: float = 0.5\n    17→const FLASH_DURATION: float = 3.0\n    18→\n    19→## Style colors matching UI style guide (identical to battery bar palette)\n    20→const COLOR_FULL := Color(\"#4ADE80\")\n    21→const COLOR_NORMAL := Color(\"#00D4AA\")\n    22→const COLOR_LOW := Color(\"#FFB830\")\n    23→const COLOR_EMPTY := Color(\"#FF6B5A\")\n    24→const COLOR_BAR_BG := Color(\"#1A2736\")\n    25→\n    26→# ── Private Variables ─────────────────────────────────────\n    27→var _fuel_percent: float = 1.0\n    28→var _is_low: bool = false\n    29→var _is_empty: bool = false\n    30→var _pulse_timer: float = 0.0\n    31→var _flash_timer: float = 0.0\n    32→var _flash_elapsed: float = 0.0\n    33→var _flash_visible: bool = true\n    34→var _font_mono: Font = null\n    35→var _bar_rect := Rect2(0, 0, 0, 0)\n    36→var _icon_texture: Texture2D = null\n    37→\n    38→# ── Built-in Virtual Methods ──────────────────────────────\n    39→\n    40→func _ready() -> void:\n    41→\tcustom_minimum_size = Vector2(TOTAL_WIDTH, TOTAL_HEIGHT)\n    42→\t_font_mono = ThemeDB.fallback_font\n    43→\t_icon_texture = load(\"res://assets/icons/item/icon_item_fuel_cell.svg\") as Texture2D\n    44→\tFuelSystem.fuel_changed.connect(_on_fuel_changed)\n    45→\tFuelSystem.fuel_low.connect(_on_fuel_low)\n    46→\tFuelSystem.fuel_empty.connect(_on_fuel_empty)\n    47→\t# Initialize from current fuel state\n    48→\t_fuel_percent = FuelSystem.fuel_current / FuelSystem.fuel_max if FuelSystem.fuel_max > 0.0 else 0.0\n    49→\n    50→func _process(delta: float) -> void:\n    51→\t_pulse_timer += delta * PULSE_SPEED\n    52→\n    53→\tif _is_empty:\n    54→\t\t_flash_elapsed += delta\n    55→\t\t_flash_timer += delta\n    56→\t\tif _flash_timer >= FLASH_INTERVAL:\n    57→\t\t\t_flash_timer = 0.0\n    58→\t\t\t_flash_visible = not _flash_visible\n    59→\t\t# After flash duration, hold at 50% opacity\n    60→\t\tif _flash_elapsed >= FLASH_DURATION:\n    61→\t\t\t_flash_visible = true\n    62→\n    63→\tqueue_redraw()\n    64→\n    65→func _draw() -> void:\n    66→\tvar x_offset: float = 0.0\n    67→\tvar y_center: float = TOTAL_HEIGHT / 2.0\n    68→\n    69→\tvar state_color: Color = _get_state_color()\n    70→\n    71→\t# Draw fuel icon\n    72→\tif _icon_texture:\n    73→\t\tvar icon_rect := Rect2(x_offset, y_center - ICON_SIZE / 2.0, ICON_SIZE, ICON_SIZE)\n    74→\t\tdraw_texture_rect(_icon_texture, icon_rect, false, state_color)\n    75→\tx_offset += ICON_SIZE + 8.0\n    76→\n    77→\t# Draw progress bar background\n    78→\t_bar_rect = Rect2(x_offset, y_center - BAR_HEIGHT / 2.0, BAR_WIDTH, BAR_HEIGHT)\n    79→\tdraw_rect(_bar_rect, COLOR_BAR_BG, true)\n    80→\n    81→\t# Draw progress bar fill\n    82→\tvar fill_width: float = BAR_WIDTH * _fuel_percent\n    83→\tif fill_width > 0 and (_flash_visible or not _is_empty):\n    84→\t\tvar fill_rect := Rect2(_bar_rect.position.x, _bar_rect.position.y, fill_width, BAR_HEIGHT)\n    85→\t\tdraw_rect(fill_rect, state_color, true)\n    86→\n    87→\tx_offset += BAR_WIDTH + 8.0\n    88→\n    89→\t# Draw percentage text\n    90→\tvar percent_text: String = get_percent_text()\n    91→\tdraw_string(\n    92→\t\t_font_mono,\n    93→\t\tVector2(x_offset, y_center + 6),\n    94→\t\tpercent_text,\n    95→\t\tHORIZONTAL_ALIGNMENT_LEFT,\n    96→\t\t-1,\n    97→\t\t18,\n    98→\t\tstate_color,\n    99→\t)\n   100→\n   101→# ── Public Methods ────────────────────────────────────────\n   102→\n   103→## Updates the fuel display from external caller. Computes percentage internally.\n   104→func set_fuel_level(current: float, maximum: float) -> void:\n   105→\t_on_fuel_changed(current, maximum)\n   106→\n   107→## Returns the formatted percentage text for the current fuel level.\n   108→func get_percent_text() -> String:\n   109→\treturn \"%d%%\" % int(_fuel_percent * 100)\n   110→\n   111→# ── Private Methods ───────────────────────────────────────\n   112→\n   113→func _get_state_color() -> Color:\n   114→\tif _is_empty or _fuel_percent <= 0.0:\n   115→\t\t# Empty state — solid coral (flash handled in _draw fill visibility)\n   116→\t\tif _is_empty and _flash_elapsed >= FLASH_DURATION:\n   117→\t\t\treturn Color(COLOR_EMPTY, 0.5)\n   118→\t\treturn COLOR_EMPTY\n   119→\telif _fuel_percent >= 1.0:\n   120→\t\treturn COLOR_FULL\n   121→\telif _is_low or _fuel_percent <= LOW_THRESHOLD:\n   122→\t\t# Low state — pulse opacity between 70% and 100% over 1.5s\n   123→\t\tvar pulse_alpha: float = 0.7 + 0.3 * (sin(_pulse_timer) * 0.5 + 0.5)\n   124→\t\treturn Color(COLOR_LOW, pulse_alpha)\n   125→\telse:\n   126→\t\treturn COLOR_NORMAL\n   127→\n   128→func _on_fuel_changed(current: float, maximum: float) -> void:\n   129→\tif maximum > 0.0:\n   130→\t\t_fuel_percent = current / maximum\n   131→\telse:\n   132→\t\t_fuel_percent = 0.0\n   133→\t# Clear state flags when fuel rises above thresholds\n   134→\tif current > 0.0:\n   135→\t\t_is_empty = false\n   136→\t\t_flash_timer = 0.0\n   137→\t\t_flash_elapsed = 0.0\n   138→\t\t_flash_visible = true\n   139→\tif _fuel_percent > LOW_THRESHOLD:\n   140→\t\t_is_low = false\n   141→\tGlobal.log(\"FuelGauge: updated to %.0f%%\" % (_fuel_percent * 100.0))\n   142→\n   143→func _on_fuel_low() -> void:\n   144→\t_is_low = true\n   145→\tGlobal.log(\"FuelGauge: LOW FUEL warning active\")\n   146→\n   147→func _on_fuel_empty() -> void:\n   148→\t_is_empty = true\n   149→\t_flash_timer = 0.0\n   150→\t_flash_elapsed = 0.0\n   151→\t_flash_visible = true\n   152→\tGlobal.log(\"FuelGauge: FUEL EMPTY — flash animation started\")\n   153→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"9a26a766-848f-4b2d-b2a6-6bc7f926a7de","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"C:\\repos\\Hammer-Forge-Studio\\.claude\\worktrees\\orch-gameplay-programmer-TICKET-0247\\game\\scripts\\ui\\fuel_gauge.gd","content":"## Fuel gauge HUD: always-visible ship fuel level display with state-driven colors.\n## Connects to FuelSystem signals (fuel_changed, fuel_low, fuel_empty) for real-time updates.\n## Four visual states: full (green), normal (teal), low (amber pulse), empty (coral flash).\n## Owner: gameplay-programmer — Ticket: TICKET-0169\nclass_name FuelGauge\nextends Control\n\n# ── Constants ─────────────────────────────────────────────\nconst BAR_WIDTH: float = 160.0\nconst BAR_HEIGHT: float = 10.0\nconst ICON_SIZE: float = 24.0\nconst TOTAL_WIDTH: float = 200.0\nconst TOTAL_HEIGHT: float = 48.0\nconst LOW_THRESHOLD: float = FuelSystemDefs.LOW_FUEL_THRESHOLD_PERCENT\nconst PULSE_SPEED: float = 4.2  # ~1.5s loop (2*PI / 1.5)\nconst FLASH_INTERVAL: float = 0.5\nconst FLASH_DURATION: float = 3.0\n\n## Style colors matching UI style guide (identical to battery bar palette)\nconst COLOR_FULL := Color(\"#4ADE80\")\nconst COLOR_NORMAL := Color(\"#00D4AA\")\nconst COLOR_LOW := Color(\"#FFB830\")\nconst COLOR_EMPTY := Color(\"#FF6B5A\")\nconst COLOR_BAR_BG := Color(\"#1A2736\")\n\n# ── Private Variables ─────────────────────────────────────\nvar _fuel_percent: float = 1.0\nvar _is_low: bool = false\nvar _is_empty: bool = false\nvar _pulse_timer: float = 0.0\nvar _flash_timer: float = 0.0\nvar _flash_elapsed: float = 0.0\nvar _flash_visible: bool = true\nvar _font_mono: Font = null\nvar _bar_rect := Rect2(0, 0, 0, 0)\nvar _icon_texture: Texture2D = null\n\n# ── Built-in Virtual Methods ──────────────────────────────\n\nfunc _ready() -> void:\n\tcustom_minimum_size = Vector2(TOTAL_WIDTH, TOTAL_HEIGHT)\n\t_font_mono = ThemeDB.fallback_font\n\t_icon_texture = load(\"res://assets/icons/item/icon_item_fuel_cell.svg\") as Texture2D\n\tFuelSystem.fuel_changed.connect(_on_fuel_changed)\n\tFuelSystem.fuel_low.connect(_on_fuel_low)\n\tFuelSystem.fuel_empty.connect(_on_fuel_empty)\n\t# Initialize from current fuel state\n\t_fuel_percent = FuelSystem.fuel_current / FuelSystem.fuel_max if FuelSystem.fuel_max > 0.0 else 0.0\n\nfunc _process(delta: float) -> void:\n\t_pulse_timer += delta * PULSE_SPEED\n\n\tif _is_empty:\n\t\t_flash_elapsed += delta\n\t\t_flash_timer += delta\n\t\tif _flash_timer >= FLASH_INTERVAL:\n\t\t\t_flash_timer = 0.0\n\t\t\t_flash_visible = not _flash_visible\n\t\t# After flash duration, hold at 50% opacity\n\t\tif _flash_elapsed >= FLASH_DURATION:\n\t\t\t_flash_visible = true\n\n\tqueue_redraw()\n\nfunc _draw() -> void:\n\tvar x_offset: float = 0.0\n\tvar y_center: float = TOTAL_HEIGHT / 2.0\n\n\tvar state_color: Color = _get_state_color()\n\n\t# Draw fuel icon\n\tif _icon_texture:\n\t\tvar icon_rect := Rect2(x_offset, y_center - ICON_SIZE / 2.0, ICON_SIZE, ICON_SIZE)\n\t\tdraw_texture_rect(_icon_texture, icon_rect, false, state_color)\n\tx_offset += ICON_SIZE + 8.0\n\n\t# Draw progress bar background\n\t_bar_rect = Rect2(x_offset, y_center - BAR_HEIGHT / 2.0, BAR_WIDTH, BAR_HEIGHT)\n\tdraw_rect(_bar_rect, COLOR_BAR_BG, true)\n\n\t# Draw progress bar fill\n\tvar fill_width: float = BAR_WIDTH * _fuel_percent\n\tif fill_width > 0 and (_flash_visible or not _is_empty):\n\t\tvar fill_rect := Rect2(_bar_rect.position.x, _bar_rect.position.y, fill_width, BAR_HEIGHT)\n\t\tdraw_rect(fill_rect, state_color, true)\n\n\tx_offset += BAR_WIDTH + 8.0\n\n\t# Draw percentage text\n\tvar percent_text: String = get_percent_text()\n\tdraw_string(\n\t\t_font_mono,\n\t\tVector2(x_offset, y_center + 6),\n\t\tpercent_text,\n\t\tHORIZONTAL_ALIGNMENT_LEFT,\n\t\t-1,\n\t\t18,\n\t\tstate_color,\n\t)\n\n# ── Public Methods ────────────────────────────────────────\n\n## Updates the fuel display from external caller. Computes percentage internally.\nfunc set_fuel_level(current: float, maximum: float) -> void:\n\t_on_fuel_changed(current, maximum)\n\n## Returns the formatted percentage text for the current fuel level.\nfunc get_percent_text() -> String:\n\treturn \"%d%%\" % int(_fuel_percent * 100)\n\n# ── Private Methods ───────────────────────────────────────\n\nfunc _get_state_color() -> Color:\n\tif _is_empty or _fuel_percent <= 0.0:\n\t\t# Empty state — solid coral (flash handled in _draw fill visibility)\n\t\tif _is_empty and _flash_elapsed >= FLASH_DURATION:\n\t\t\treturn Color(COLOR_EMPTY, 0.5)\n\t\treturn COLOR_EMPTY\n\telif _fuel_percent >= 1.0:\n\t\treturn COLOR_FULL\n\telif _is_low or _fuel_percent <= LOW_THRESHOLD:\n\t\t# Low state — pulse opacity between 70% and 100% over 1.5s\n\t\tvar pulse_alpha: float = 0.7 + 0.3 * (sin(_pulse_timer) * 0.5 + 0.5)\n\t\treturn Color(COLOR_LOW, pulse_alpha)\n\telse:\n\t\treturn COLOR_NORMAL\n\nfunc _on_fuel_changed(current: float, maximum: float) -> void:\n\tif maximum > 0.0:\n\t\t_fuel_percent = current / maximum\n\telse:\n\t\t_fuel_percent = 0.0\n\t# Clear state flags when fuel rises above thresholds\n\tif current > 0.0:\n\t\t_is_empty = false\n\t\t_flash_timer = 0.0\n\t\t_flash_elapsed = 0.0\n\t\t_flash_visible = true\n\tif _fuel_percent > LOW_THRESHOLD:\n\t\t_is_low = false\n\tGlobal.log(\"FuelGauge: updated to %.0f%%\" % (_fuel_percent * 100.0))\n\nfunc _on_fuel_low() -> void:\n\t_is_low = true\n\tGlobal.log(\"FuelGauge: LOW FUEL warning active\")\n\nfunc _on_fuel_empty() -> void:\n\t_is_empty = true\n\t_flash_timer = 0.0\n\t_flash_elapsed = 0.0\n\t_flash_visible = true\n\tGlobal.log(\"FuelGauge: FUEL EMPTY — flash animation started\")\n","numLines":153,"startLine":1,"totalLines":153}}},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01YH1CeyRL1uR9XCPGb7MEdh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, the FuelGauge signal handlers are benign — they just update UI state variables. They don't cause any re-entrant calls or side effects that would break the travel flow.\n\nLet me take a completely different approach. Instead of trying to find the bug through pure analysis, let me look at what the actual state of the `NavigationConsole` process_mode is. The NavigationConsole has `process_mode = Node.PROCESS_MODE_INHERIT`. Its parent is... let me check how it's added to the tree.\n\nActually, wait. Looking at test_world.gd:\n```gdscript_navigation_console = _hud.get_navigation_console()```\n\n\nSo the NavigationConsole is obtained from the HUD, which means it's nested under TestWorld/HUD/, not at the same level as TravelSequenceManager. I've been going in circles trying to trace through the code — let me shift tactics and consider whether `initiate_travel()` might be returning early without actually starting the async sequence.\n\nNow I'm checking what could cause those early returns: the state might be stuck in a non-IDLE status from a previous failed attempt, the biome ID could be invalid, the destination might somehow match the current biome, or the fuel check could be failing. For that last one, the weight calculation after the wave 1 fix should be BASE_SHIP_WEIGHT plus module weight, but I need to verify what's actually being computed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2437,"cache_read_input_tokens":114999,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2437},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"d762eb11-7472-4174-b6c1-d11d2517d863"},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01YH1CeyRL1uR9XCPGb7MEdh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01VN2J8TLWhTrkDkfwgM7gke","name":"Grep","input":{"pattern":"class_name FuelSystemDefs","glob":"*.gd"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2437,"cache_read_input_tokens":114999,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2437},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"50d6a8d7-bc67-4872-b942-b441a946869f"},{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VN2J8TLWhTrkDkfwgM7gke","type":"tool_result","content":"Found 1 file\ngame\\scripts\\data\\fuel_system_defs.gd"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"acbc5bd3-976b-4c2b-a4d6-a3cf65de4de7","tool_use_result":{"mode":"files_with_matches","filenames":["game\\scripts\\data\\fuel_system_defs.gd"],"numFiles":1}},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0122Axbz3eJUj5XKrhGPt6ty","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01JbWfhVRe7JvgLT89U8ZDDM","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\repos\\Hammer-Forge-Studio\\.claude\\worktrees\\orch-gameplay-programmer-TICKET-0247\\game\\scripts\\data\\fuel_system_defs.gd"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":645,"cache_read_input_tokens":117436,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":645},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"9fb7e652-ae12-42f9-8998-98adfd40a84e"},{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JbWfhVRe7JvgLT89U8ZDDM","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→## Canonical data definitions for the ship fuel system.\n     2→## All tunable fuel constants live here — nothing is hardcoded in FuelSystem logic.\n     3→## Ticket: TICKET-0158\n     4→class_name FuelSystemDefs\n     5→extends RefCounted\n     6→\n     7→# ── Constants ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n     8→\n     9→## Maximum fuel the ship tank can hold, in fuel units.\n    10→const FUEL_TANK_CAPACITY: float = 1000.0\n    11→\n    12→## Fuel units provided by a single Fuel Cell when refueling.\n    13→## Tune this to adjust how many jumps a stack of Fuel Cells covers.\n    14→const FUEL_CELL_UNITS: float = 100.0\n    15→\n    16→## Fraction of max fuel at or below which the low-fuel signal fires (25%).\n    17→const LOW_FUEL_THRESHOLD_PERCENT: float = 0.25\n    18→\n    19→## Fuel cost multiplier: fuel units per weight unit per distance unit.\n    20→## Formula: cost = distance * ship_weight * FUEL_COST_MULTIPLIER\n    21→## With default values: 1000 distance * 50 weight * 0.005 = 250 fuel per jump.\n    22→const FUEL_COST_MULTIPLIER: float = 0.005\n    23→\n    24→## Base ship weight — the ship's empty mass before modules or cargo.\n    25→## Ensures a non-zero travel cost even when nothing is installed.\n    26→const BASE_SHIP_WEIGHT: int = 50\n    27→\n    28→## Weight units contributed by each installed ship module.\n    29→const WEIGHT_PER_MODULE: int = 10\n    30→\n    31→## Weight units contributed by each item in the player inventory.\n    32→## Set to 0: inventory items no longer inflate fuel costs. Previously set to 1,\n    33→## which caused travel costs to exceed tank capacity as the player gathered\n    34→## resources (TICKET-0247).\n    35→const WEIGHT_PER_INVENTORY_ITEM: int = 0\n    36→\n    37→## Placeholder biome travel distance used for testing and dev until the biome\n    38→## registry (TICKET-0159) defines real distances.\n    39→const BIOME_DISTANCE_PLACEHOLDER: float = 1000.0\n    40→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"424340cd-543e-4b13-831d-fcba1bc782db","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"C:\\repos\\Hammer-Forge-Studio\\.claude\\worktrees\\orch-gameplay-programmer-TICKET-0247\\game\\scripts\\data\\fuel_system_defs.gd","content":"## Canonical data definitions for the ship fuel system.\n## All tunable fuel constants live here — nothing is hardcoded in FuelSystem logic.\n## Ticket: TICKET-0158\nclass_name FuelSystemDefs\nextends RefCounted\n\n# ── Constants ─────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n## Maximum fuel the ship tank can hold, in fuel units.\nconst FUEL_TANK_CAPACITY: float = 1000.0\n\n## Fuel units provided by a single Fuel Cell when refueling.\n## Tune this to adjust how many jumps a stack of Fuel Cells covers.\nconst FUEL_CELL_UNITS: float = 100.0\n\n## Fraction of max fuel at or below which the low-fuel signal fires (25%).\nconst LOW_FUEL_THRESHOLD_PERCENT: float = 0.25\n\n## Fuel cost multiplier: fuel units per weight unit per distance unit.\n## Formula: cost = distance * ship_weight * FUEL_COST_MULTIPLIER\n## With default values: 1000 distance * 50 weight * 0.005 = 250 fuel per jump.\nconst FUEL_COST_MULTIPLIER: float = 0.005\n\n## Base ship weight — the ship's empty mass before modules or cargo.\n## Ensures a non-zero travel cost even when nothing is installed.\nconst BASE_SHIP_WEIGHT: int = 50\n\n## Weight units contributed by each installed ship module.\nconst WEIGHT_PER_MODULE: int = 10\n\n## Weight units contributed by each item in the player inventory.\n## Set to 0: inventory items no longer inflate fuel costs. Previously set to 1,\n## which caused travel costs to exceed tank capacity as the player gathered\n## resources (TICKET-0247).\nconst WEIGHT_PER_INVENTORY_ITEM: int = 0\n\n## Placeholder biome travel distance used for testing and dev until the biome\n## registry (TICKET-0159) defines real distances.\nconst BIOME_DISTANCE_PLACEHOLDER: float = 1000.0\n","numLines":40,"startLine":1,"totalLines":40}}},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_016J7VJabbgw4pFEgw1YyCHW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, the fuel system defs look correct. With BASE_SHIP_WEIGHT=50, WEIGHT_PER_INVENTORY_ITEM=0, FUEL_COST_MULTIPLIER=0.005, and BIOME_DISTANCE_PLACEHOLDER=1000.0:\n\nCost = 1000 * 50 * 0.005 = 250 fuel units\n\nFull tank = 1000 fuel units. So you can afford the travel.\n\n`can_travel_to()` should return true if the tank has >= 250 units. With a full tank (1000), this passes.\n\nLet me now check if there's ANYTHING in the actual flow that I've been missing. \n\nI need to trace through the input handling more carefully—specifically what happens when the confirm button gets pressed through the `_input` method and how that triggers the travel flow.\n\nLooking at the input handler, when `ui_accept` is pressed and the confirm button has focus, it calls `_on_confirm_pressed()`. This method checks if a biome is selected and if travel is allowed, then calls `_close_for_travel()` to set `_is_open = false` before initiating travel.\n\nThere's also a direct signal connection from the button's `pressed` signal to the same handler. If a mouse click generates both a button press and a `ui_accept` input action, both paths could theoretically fire—but the first call sets `_is_open = false`, so the second call would exit early and never execute the travel logic.\n\nI've been analyzing the code flow, but it should work based on my logic. The tests pass, yet the symptom persists: inputs stay disabled with no fade and no scene change. My leading theory is that the `_on_travel_completed` coroutine is hanging when it awaits the fade-out animation, likely because `create_tween()` isn't completing as expected.\n\nNow I'm examining the `_fade_out()` function more closely—specifically whether `create_tween()` is properly initialized on the TravelSequenceManager node.\n\nIn Godot 4, `create_tween()` automatically starts processing on the next frame and is reference-counted, so the tween shouldn't be garbage collected while `await tween.finished` is holding a reference to it. There's no explicit `kill()` call that would terminate it prematurely, so the tween should complete normally unless something else is interrupting the signal chain or the node is being freed during the fade.\n\nActually, wait—maybe the real problem is simpler. The player says they're locked in place but nothing happens after clicking CONFIRM TRAVEL. What if the NavigationConsole's dim rect is still blocking the view? The `_animate_close()` should fade it out over 0.15 seconds, so the game world should become visible again. Then after 0.5 seconds, the TravelSequenceManager's fade overlay should fade in with a black screen. But if the fade_rect isn't displaying properly—maybe it's behind something, or maybe its initial alpha is preventing the fade from being visible—the player would just see the locked state without any visual feedback of the transition happening.\n\nLet me look more carefully at the `_animate_close()` function to see what's actually being animated.\n\nExamining the animation code...\n\nSo the close animation fades out the dim rect and main panel over 0.15 seconds, then sets the console to invisible. But here's the thing — when you call `create_tween()` in Godot 4, it automatically kills any previously running tweens on that node. So if the open animation is still running when close gets called, the open tween would be interrupted and killed, which could leave the console in a partially-animated state.\n\nWait, let me reconsider — actually, in Godot 4 they changed this behavior. Multiple tweens can coexist on the same node now, so `_animate_close()` creating a new tween wouldn't kill the existing ones. That means the open and close animations could theoretically run simultaneously if the timing is off.\n\nNow I'm wondering if the real issue is the timing of when `visible = false` gets called. The tween callback is scheduled for the end of the animation, but the tween doesn't actually process until the next frame. So there's a window where the callback hasn't fired yet, but `initiate_travel()` might already be running.\n\nLet me trace through the frame-by-frame execution: when `_on_confirm_pressed` fires, it creates the close tween (which won't process yet), then immediately calls `initiate_travel()` synchronously. That triggers `travel_completed`, which runs `_on_travel_completed` and creates another tween for the fade. Both tweens are now queued but haven't started processing. Only on the next frame do they both begin animating in parallel.\n\nActually, I just realized something important here.\n\nThe NavigationConsole's `_input` handler checks if the console is open and returns early if it's not. After `_close_for_travel()` sets `_is_open` to false, the handler stops processing input events. But TestWorld also has its own `_input` handler that manages mouse mode toggling for the pause action, and that one doesn't have any guards checking the console state.\n\nI've been digging into this for a while now. Let me think about what's most likely causing the hang based on the producer's hint about reordering the close before travel. The issue is probably one of three things: `initiate_travel()` is returning early without doing anything, the fade animation is getting stuck, or something in the biome swap is crashing silently. Rather than hunt for the exact bug, I should add logging throughout the travel sequence and make the flow more defensive with proper error handling.\n\nWait, let me reconsider the producer's note about input being disabled. They said it happens inside `_on_travel_completed`, but actually the input was already locked when the panel opened. Let me trace through what's actually happening here.\n\nThe real question is whether `_on_travel_completed` is even firing. If `initiate_travel()` returns early before emitting the signal, or if the signal connection somehow broke, that would explain why the transition never happens. The connection gets set up in `setup()` during `_ready()`, and nothing disconnects it except in tests, so that's probably not it. But what if `initiate_travel()` is emitting the signal but something else is preventing the transition from completing?\n\nWait — what if the fade is actually working, but the player can't see it because they're inside the ship interior, which is positioned way below the main scene? The CanvasLayer for the fade is at layer 10, so it should render on top regardless of position, unless the ship interior has its own CanvasLayer above it. That seems unlikely though.\n\nI think I need to stop theorizing and just add some defensive logging to trace what's actually happening, then try a different approach to make sure the transition works reliably.\n\nActually, let me look at the confirm handler one more time — I'm checking the destination selection and validation, then emitting the travel signal and starting to close the panel...\n\nWait, I need to trace through what happens when `_close_for_travel()` runs. It triggers an animation that creates a tween bound to the NavigationConsole node itself. But then `NavigationSystem.initiate_travel()` runs synchronously and starts its own state machine, which eventually emits `travel_completed`. The TravelSequenceManager listens for that signal and handles the actual biome transition with its own async sequence. So the question is whether the NavigationConsole's tween stays alive and bound to the node during all of this, or if something else is managing the lifecycle here. I see the issue now—in Godot 4, `create_tween()` doesn't automatically kill previous tweens, so multiple tweens can run simultaneously on the same node. When two tweens target the same property, they'll both try to animate it at once, which causes conflicts.\n\nIn this case, `_animate_open()` and `_animate_close()` both target `_dim_rect.modulate:a` and `_main_panel.modulate:a`. If the close animation starts before the open animation finishes, they'd fight over those properties. But since the open tween only takes 0.2 seconds and the player needs time to select and confirm, the open should complete well before close starts.\n\nLet me think about this differently though—what if `_close_for_travel()` isn't being called at all? If the `_is_open` check is somehow false when it should be true, the function would return early and nothing would happen.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the player could press ESC to close the panel between selecting a destination and clicking confirm. The input handler checks if the panel is open, and if ESC is pressed, it calls `close_panel()` which sets `_is_open` to false. So if that happens, the confirm button would no longer be clickable, but let me trace through what happens if somehow the close gets triggered anyway.\n\nWait, I'm going down a rabbit hole here. Let me pivot to something else entirely—what if `_on_travel_completed` actually fires and the fade works and the biome swaps, but the new scene loads with no visible content? The player would see the fade-out go black, then fade back in to an empty or invisible scene. But the producer said there's no fade at all, no scene change, nothing visible. If the fade-out happened, they'd definitely see the screen go black, so that doesn't match what they're reporting.\n\nLet me reconsider the `_close_for_travel()` method and whether it could somehow block `_on_travel_completed` from executing. The method triggers an animation that sets the UI layer to invisible via a callback, but that shouldn't affect other nodes or prevent signals from firing. Actually, I need to check what `visible` refers to in that callback lambda—it should be capturing `self`, which is the NavigationConsole itself.\n\nSo setting `visible = false` on the CanvasLayer just hides it visually without affecting the scene tree or signal processing. At this point, I think the best approach is to add comprehensive logging throughout the flow and make the code more defensive—handle potential null references, add a timeout fallback in case the fade doesn't complete, and restructure things so the travel logic is more robust.\n\nWait, I'm wondering if the real issue is simpler: maybe the NavigationConsole's `_input` handler and the button's `pressed` signal are both firing for the same click. But no, the `_input` handler calls `set_input_as_handled()` to stop propagation, and besides, UI controls process input before `_input` methods anyway, so the button would fire first and the input handler would see an already-handled event.\n\nActually, I need to verify the exact input processing order in Godot 4 — I'm second-guessing myself on whether `_input` runs before or after GUI controls handle their input. First, `_input()` is called on all nodes in the tree, from the viewport down. If the event is not handled, it goes to the Control nodes for GUI handling. If still not handled, `_unhandled_input()` is called.\n\nActually, I think the order in Godot 4 is: `Node._input()` virtual method fires top-down from root, then if not handled, GUI input processing happens with Control nodes, and finally if still not handled, `Node._unhandled_input()` fires top-down from root. So `NavigationConsole._input()` fires BEFORE the button's `pressed` signal.\n\nLet me trace what happens when the player presses the \"Enter\" key while the confirm button has focus. My `_input()` method checks if the console is open, and if ui_accept is pressed with the confirm button focused and enabled, it calls `_on_confirm_pressed()` and marks the event as handled. This runs the full travel flow and sets `_is_open` to false. Since the event is already handled, the GUI input processing and `_unhandled_input()` don't trigger, so `_on_confirm_pressed()` is called exactly once with keyboard input.\n\nNow I need to figure out what happens with mouse clicks. I'm realizing the issue now — in the test setup, `_manager` isn't added to the scene tree, and neither is `_container`. When `_build_fade_overlay()` runs, it checks `is_inside_tree()` and returns early since the manager isn't in the tree, so the fade overlay never actually gets built.\n\nThen when `initiate_travel()` is called and eventually triggers `_on_travel_completed()`, it awaits `_fade_out()`, but since `_fade_rect` is null, the fade-out function returns immediately without blocking — the await completes right away rather than hanging forever. In GDScript 4, `_fade_out()` is a function that has `await` on one code path. GDScript compiles this as a coroutine. When called, it returns a Signal (the coroutine's completion signal). When `_fade_out()` takes the early return path (before hitting its `await`), it completes synchronously. The completion signal is emitted immediately (or is already in a \"completed\" state). In the caller: `await _fade_out()` awaits this completion signal. Since the signal is already completed (synchronous return), the `await` resolves immediately (or on the next engine step, I'm not 100% sure). The key question is whether `await` on an already-completed coroutine resolves in the same frame or defers to the next frame.\n\nIf it resolves immediately in the same frame, then the entire sequence runs synchronously: biome swap executes, fade in returns early, inputs get re-enabled, the transition flag clears, and both completion signals fire before control returns to `initiate_travel()`. All test assertions would pass.\n\nIf it defers to the next frame, then after `await _fade_out()` completes, the coroutine suspends and control returns back up to `initiate_travel()`, which changes the timing of when everything else happens.\n\nThe test code is checking the biome node after calling `initiate_travel()`, so I need to see whether the test expects the biome to have changed immediately or if it's written to handle deferred execution.\n\nLooking at the test, it calls `initiate_travel()` and then immediately retrieves and asserts on the current biome node. Since the test passes, this means the biome must have updated synchronously—which tells me that in GDScript 4, awaiting a coroutine that completes early (via early return) resolves immediately in the same frame without deferring to the next frame.\n\nSo in the actual game where the fade animation exists, `await tween.finished` genuinely suspends execution for 0.5 seconds while the tween runs, then resumes afterward.\n\nThe tweens themselves don't conflict since `_animate_close()` modifies properties on NavigationConsole's children while `_fade_out()` modifies properties on TravelSequenceManager's children—they're operating on completely separate node hierarchies.\n\nGiven the symptom where inputs lock but the biome transition never fires, I'm thinking the issue is either a Godot 4 runtime quirk where the tween doesn't actually complete in this specific context, or `initiate_travel()` is hitting an early return we're not seeing. My instinct is to bypass the signal-await chain entirely by having NavigationConsole call the travel method directly on TravelSequenceManager, though that's a bigger refactor than I'd prefer.\n\nActually, looking at the producer notes again—the player sees nothing after clicking CONFIRM TRAVEL. I'm wondering if the fade is actually working but the new biome is rendering as a black screen, which would be invisible against the black fade overlay. But that contradicts \"no fade\" in the symptom. Unless the fade rect itself isn't visible for some reason—let me trace through the setup: the rect is black, modulate alpha starts at 0 and tweens to 1, so it should definitely show. But what if there's something wrong with the rect's visibility or layer setup?\n\nActually, I think I've found it. The real problem is probably that `await tween.finished` inside `_fade_out()` is hanging when called from the signal handler chain, which would freeze the whole sequence and leave inputs disabled. My solution is to decouple the flow—instead of having the navigation console directly trigger the travel system (which emits the signal synchronously and kicks off the async fade), I'll restructure it so the fade completes properly before the biome swap happens.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to use `call_deferred` in the signal handler, which pushes the actual transition logic to the next frame and breaks it out of the nested call stack where the tween might be getting stuck.\n\nImplementing the deferred handler... I'm wondering if coroutines in signal handlers actually work in Godot 4, or if there's an edge case I'm missing. Maybe the real problem is that `create_tween()` is failing silently when called inside `_fade_out()` — if the node isn't in the tree, it returns null and then trying to call methods on it would crash. But we're already checking `is_inside_tree()` before that, so it should be fine... unless there's something about how `get_tree().create_tween()` works internally that I'm not accounting for.\n\nLet me just go ahead with my fix and add some logging to help debug if this keeps happening. Actually, wait — before I commit to anything, let me check one more time if there's a simple typo or logic error I've been missing. I'm going to carefully re-read the `_on_travel_completed` function to see if something obvious jumps out.\n\nThe function fades to black, executes the biome swap, and if that fails it fades back in and restores the input state before returning early. Otherwise it fades back in, re-enables input, marks the transition as complete, and emits the completion signal.\n\nNow I'm looking at the fade helper functions — they create tweens that animate the fade rectangle's opacity over a set duration, with `_fade_out` bringing it to full opacity and `_fade_in` bringing it back to transparent.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a potential issue: if `_fade_rect` is null, the function returns early without awaiting anything, so the caller gets an immediate resolution. However, if the tween is created but then killed (like when the node exits the tree), the `finished` signal might never fire, causing the await to hang indefinitely.\n\nLet me trace through the actual scenario — TravelSequenceManager is a child of TestWorld, not `_biome_container`, so it shouldn't be removed during `_clear_biome_container()`. But I need to check if `execute_biome_swap()` does something else that could interrupt the tween.\n\nActually, I should verify whether the SceneTree itself is being paused somewhere. The `_input` handler checks for a pause action but doesn't actually set `get_tree().paused`, so that's probably not the issue.\n\nNow I'm wondering about the NavigationConsole's process_mode — it's set to inherit from its parent. The NavigationConsole is a CanvasLayer obtained from the HUD, and CanvasLayers are rendering layers that can affect their children's processing. But TravelSequenceManager isn't a child of NavigationConsole anyway, it's under TestWorld, so that shouldn't matter either.\n\nLet me just fix this directly. I'll use `call_deferred` in `_on_travel_completed` to run the async transition in a clean call stack, avoiding any complications with `await` nested deep in signal handlers. I should also add a timeout safety check — if the fade tween doesn't finish within a reasonable time, force it to