now about TravelSequenceManager, and TravelSequenceManager would call NavigationSystem. Let me trace through the dependencies to see if this actually works. requires the NavigationConsole to have a reference to TravelSequenceManager. Currently it doesn't.\n\nAnother approach: have NavigationConsole call `NavigationSystem.initiate_travel()` as before, but make the TravelSequenceManager's handler start a separate coroutine instead of being one itself. The handler would call a method that contains the await logic, keeping the signal handler non-blocking.\n\nBut wait, that's essentially the same structure we already have. The real issue might be that `_start_travel_transition` is a coroutine being called from within a signal handler. I'm wondering if there's actually a meaningful difference between awaiting directly in the signal handler versus calling a separate coroutine method from it. In both cases, the coroutine suspends at the same point when it hits an await statement.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully: if the signal handler itself is a coroutine that awaits, it suspends inside the handler. If the handler calls a separate coroutine without awaiting it, the handler returns immediately while the coroutine runs independently. That's the key difference—the signal handler completes synchronously in the second case, which might avoid whatever issue is occurring with suspending inside the handler itself.\n\nBut in the tests, both approaches should behave the same way since `_fade_out()` returns synchronously anyway. Whether `_on_travel_completed` is a coroutine that awaits `_fade_out()`, or a regular function that calls a coroutine that awaits `_fade_out()`, the test should still pass because everything resolves in one frame.\n\nThe real benefit shows up in the actual game: by moving the async work into a separate coroutine that isn't a signal handler, I avoid keeping the handler suspended. The handler returns cleanly while the transition logic runs independently, which is a cleaner pattern.\n\nI'll split `_on_travel_completed` into a non-coroutine handler that kicks off a separate coroutine worker.\n\nNow I'm checking whether the tests will still pass by tracing through the flow: when `initiate_travel()` is called, it emits the signal, which triggers the handler, which then starts the coroutine. But I need to verify what happens in GDScript 4 when you call a coroutine without awaiting it—does it execute immediately or get scheduled?\n\nLooking at this more carefully, if `_fade_out()` and `_fade_in()` both return synchronously in the test environment, then the entire `_start_travel_transition()` coroutine would execute to completion in a single frame, making the whole sequence happen synchronously and allowing the test to pass.\n\nThe key insight is that `_on_travel_completed` calls `_start_travel_transition` without awaiting it, so the signal handlers return immediately while the transition runs asynchronously in the background. This is fine because the signal emitters don't need to wait for the visual transition to complete.\n\nHowever, I need to make sure `_is_transitioning` is set to true before calling `_start_travel_transition`, so if the signal fires again during the transition, the handler returns early and prevents duplicate transitions.\n\nLooking at the existing logging, I can see the flow is already well-tracked through NavigationConsole and TravelSequenceManager, so I'll focus on ensuring the guard logic is properly placed. If `initiate_travel()` runs synchronously and the signal fires during that call, the log would show up after travel starts, which is fine. But if `_on_travel_completed` never fires due to a disconnected signal, I'd see logs 1-7 and 9 without 8, which would pinpoint the issue. I'm adding logging before and after the `travel_completed.emit()` call to confirm the signal actually fires and help debug similar problems down the line. Now let me implement the fix. I'm wondering if the issue is that the coroutine gets suspended when it awaits, and then the SceneTree can't resume it properly after the signal context is gone—but actually, in Godot 4 the SceneTree maintains references to suspended coroutines independently, so that shouldn't be the problem. Either way, splitting the signal handler into a non-coroutine wrapper that calls a separate coroutine worker is a proven pattern in Godot 4 and should eliminate any edge cases, so I'll implement that approach now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":722,"cache_read_input_tokens":118081,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":722},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e95448fc-7558-4157-960a-6c7229146ac9","uuid":"63d71f16-909e-4e85-853a-fc3c8a05f0e6"},{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_016J7VJabbgw4pFEgw1YyCHW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01BgCuWTFwu3chJL1wkYvzUd","name":"TodoWrite","input":{"todos":[{"content":"Read ticket and verify dependencies/status","status":"completed","activeForm":"Reading ticket and verifying dependencies"},{"content":"Investigate travel sequence code (NavigationSystem, TravelSequenceManager, navigation_console)","status":"completed","activeForm":"Investigating travel sequence code"},{"content":"Identify and fix root cause of biome transition not triggering","status":"in_progress","activeForm":"Fixing root cause of biome transition failure"},{"content":"Verify all acceptance criteria met","status":"pending","activeForm":"Verifying acceptance criteria"},{"content":"Commit, push, create PR, and update ticket","status":"pending","activeForm":"Committing and pushing changes"}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_inpu